title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 1897 12 gauge M97 Take Down
postcontent:
The Winchester Model 1897, or M97, is a classic Winchester take down shotgun built in 1912 chambered for 2 3/4 shells.  This is the platform that was invented by John Moses Browning.  It was very popular with American GI's in WWI, and it's use was protested by Germany because they felt it caused unnecessary suffering to those on the receiving end. (I found that quite amusing that anyone, or any country for that matter, would protest the use of a weapon because it would cause excessive suffering.....it's a war not a chess match right?  LOL)  You can see the finish in the pictures.  It's developed a pretty nice patina over the years.  There is one small rust spot about the size of a skittle candy on the barrel.  Inside the bore shows it's age and has some wear from years of use, but there are no visible nasty areas that I can see. (I don't have a bore scope so I have looked down the barrel using a flashing to illuminate it which is the best I can do with what I have on hand)  The forearm wood shows a good amount of usage wear, but is still intact with one 3 inch crack.  The stock itself is in decent shape, with one small hairline crack about 1 inch long.  The butt plate also has a crack. Mechanically it functions normally, the action is tight and crisp as it should be.  Inside the chamber shows normal usage wear patterns, nothing out of the ordinary for a 101 year old shotgun.  These guns are becoming more and more rare nowadays.  I have many pictures, these ads only allow for up to 3 pictures.  More available upon request, and I can take pictures of any particular part wanted.  $400 cash only, no trades.  

Also, I have had several inquiries about shipping this shotgun and out of state buyers wanting to pick it up face to face.  Current BATFE rules and regulations state I CANNOT sell a firearm to anyone not a resident of my home state (GA) without going through a licensed FFL dealer and filling out a form 4473.  I can ship it to your local FFL dealer of choice after receiving a copy of the FFL dealers license, and the buyer will have to pay the $25 outgoing FFL transfer fee from my local dealer.  It is C&R eligible.

Anyone who would like to see this shotgun in person is welcome to email and setup a time to do so. All meetings to view will take place locally at Bullseye Marksman Gun Club in Cumming, right off GA400 exit 13. I will need to see at a minimum a GA drivers license. This shotgun is listed by the BATFE as C&R eligible, so those holding a C&R license may have it shipped directly to them. Anyone else wanting shipping not holding a C&R license will have to use an FFL licensed dealer. As long as the ad is still up, the shotgun is still available.
